 bearers moved in the early 18th century to the Palatinate in Germany, Alsace in France, and (finally) to PA in the US. Its original Swiss German form is <i>Lehmann</i>. Among the American Mennonites it is also established in the altered forms <i>Layman</i> and <i>Leaman</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lhamon","meanings":["Altered form of German   Lehman  ."]},{"name":"Lehmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Heinz, Hans, Otto, Erwin, Fritz, Klaus, Gerhard, Arno, Gunter, Juergen, Almut.","German: status name for a feudal tenant or vassal, Middle High German <i>lēheman</i>, <i>lēnman</i> (from <i>lēhen</i> ‘to hold land as a feudal tenant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’). The tenant held land on loan for the duration of his life in return for rent or service, but was not free to transfer or divide it. See also   Lehman  .","Jewish (western Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Lehmann</i>, perhaps related to   Leo   3."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die du